        <p style="font-size: 0.7rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light); margin-top: 0.4rem; text-align: center;">
          Projected water level maps for 2030, 2040, and 2050 under SSP scenarios (Delft3D).
        </p>
      </div>
      <div style="flex: 1; min-width: 0;">
        <h4 class="research-paper-title"><a href="https://doi.org/10.5194/egusphere-egu26-17766" target="_blank" style="color: inherit;">Hydrodynamic Changes of Estuarine Islands in the Meghna River</a></h4>
        <p style="margin: -0.3rem 0 0.7rem;">
          <img src="{{ '/assets/img/EGU26_logo.jpg' | relative_url }}" alt="EGU26" style="height: 1.6em; vertical-align: middle; margin-right: 0.5em; border-radius: 3px;"><span style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light);">EGU General Assembly 2026</span>
        </p>
        <p>
          This study analyses long-term hydrodynamic changes across seven estuarine islands in the
          <strong>Meghna Estuary</strong> under future climate scenarios, using <strong>Delft3D</strong> simulations for 2000, 2024, and 2050.
        </p>
        <p>
          Future discharge was generated from <strong>MIROC6</strong> projections under <strong>SSP2-4.5</strong> and
          <strong>SSP5-8.5</strong>, bias-corrected and routed through <strong>HEC-HMS</strong>. High tides near Char Kukri Mukri are projected to
          rise by <strong>30–35 cm</strong> and water depths around Hatiya and Manipura by <strong>0.5–0.8 m</strong> by 2050.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light);">
          <em>Presented — EGU General Assembly 2026</em>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Feni SAR — text LEFT, images RIGHT -->
  <div style="margin-bottom: 2.2rem;">
    <div class="research-flex-row" style="display: flex; gap: 1.8rem; align-items: flex-start;">
      <div style="flex: 1; min-width: 0;">
        <h4 class="research-paper-title"><a href="https://doi.org/10.5194/egusphere-egu26-13958" target="_blank" style="color: inherit;">Post-Flood Sediment Deposition Analysis Using SAR Interferometry</a></h4>
        <p style="margin: -0.3rem 0 0.7rem;">
          <img src="{{ '/assets/img/EGU26_logo.jpg' | relative_url }}" alt="EGU26" style="height: 1.6em; vertical-align: middle; margin-right: 0.5em; border-radius: 3px;"><span style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light);">EGU General Assembly 2026</span>
        </p>
        <p>
          This study quantifies post-flood sediment deposition in the <strong>Feni floodplain</strong>, Bangladesh, following the catastrophic August 2024 flood triggered by overflow from the <strong>Dumboor dam</strong> in Tripura state.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>SAR Interferometry</strong> using <strong>Sentinel-1</strong> SLC products was applied in <strong>SNAP</strong> to generate Digital Elevation Models before and after the flood. Eight cross-section profiles in <strong>HEC-RAS</strong> revealed an average sediment deposition of <strong>2.7 cm</strong> and a maximum of <strong>7.5 cm</strong> across the region.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light);">
          <em>Presented — EGU General Assembly 2026</em>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="research-img-col" style="flex-shrink: 0; width: 340px;">
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem;">
          <img
