      <div style="flex: 1; min-width: 0;">
        <h4 class="research-paper-title"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s41024-025-00632-6" target="_blank" style="color: inherit;">Structural Dynamics of Cooling Towers</a></h4>
        <p style="margin: -0.3rem 0 0.7rem;">
          <img src="{{ '/assets/img/springer_logo.png' | relative_url }}" alt="Springer" style="height: 1.6em; vertical-align: middle; margin-right: 0.5em;"><span style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light);">Journal of Building Pathology and Rehabilitation, Springer</span>
        </p>
        <p>
          My primary research investigates the dynamic behaviour of large-scale hyperbolic cooling towers under seismic and wind loading, with a focus
          on the <strong>Rooppur Nuclear Power Plant</strong>, Bangladesh's first nuclear power plant, situated near the seismically active Madhupur
          Fault.
        </p>
        <p>
          Using <strong>ABAQUS</strong>, I compared two column modelling strategies, <strong>Embedded Reinforcement</strong> and
          <strong>Simplified Timoshenko Beam</strong>, subjecting both to the 2001 Bhuj/Kachchh earthquake (non-linear time history) and wind loads
          via Greiner's equation (BNBC-2020).
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light);">
          <em>Published — Journal of Building Pathology and Rehabilitation, Springer, 2025</em>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- uPVC — text LEFT, images RIGHT -->
  <div style="margin-bottom: 2.2rem;">
    <div class="research-flex-row" style="display: flex; gap: 1.8rem; align-items: flex-start;">
      <div style="flex: 1; min-width: 0;">
        <h4 class="research-paper-title">Impact Behaviour of Pressurised uPVC Pipes</h4>
        <p>
          This study examines the low-velocity lateral impact response of water-pressurised
          <strong>uPVC pipes</strong> under <strong>both-ends-clamped</strong> and <strong>one-clamped-one-roller</strong> support conditions, across
          four drop heights (1.0–2.75 m), using a locally built <strong>ESP32-based pressure and velocity measuring unit</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Clamped supports yielded up to <strong>6.34%</strong> higher peak contact force. Internal pressure reached <strong>3063 kPa</strong> at 2.75
          m drop. FEA matched experiment within ~14%.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--global-text-color-light);">
          <em>Under Review, 2025</em>
        </p>
